18. To what: extent this assimilation of quantity to a preceding shorb syllable was carried out in pronunciation would depend partly on the speaker himself. An educated man would be less prone to slur or weaken his syllables than an uneducated. The same speaker in ordinary careless talk would pay less regard to their due, quanti- tative pronunciation than he would in formal, ceremonious discourse.
